{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 You do not have to update Node or Parent ID on an XML Data Source. These are internal fields that are used by Magic to construct the view. They are not stored in the XML, and you do not have to select them in your task.\par
\par
In this example, you can create Contacts and multiple phone numbers. However, the Node and Parent IDs are visible, to give you an idea what is going on. The tasks themselves do not update the fields or do anything with them.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 In this view you can see the Node and Parent ID fields.\par
\par
These are essentially random fields, and do not show up in the XML. You do not have to do anything with them. You do not even have to select them within your task.\par
\par
This works because within the XML view is a \cf2 Linking field\cf1 . These fields are prefaced by a '/' and are not actually "in" the record. While they show up in the record view, they are actually a field in the parent record. In this example, \cf2 /Record_ID \cf1 is the linking field for the Phone Numbers.\par
}
